VALUES
(43, 7, 48, 40, 11, 25, 25, NULL, 'Connection of Belief and Revelation', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the ''wise and prudent'' who do not believe and the ''babes'' to whom truths are revealed. Both passages emphasize the theme of belief in Jesus being limited to those who are humble rather than the learned.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 48, 44, 6, 7, 7, 'rulers or of the Pharisees believed', 'Belief Among Rulers and Priests', 'This connection highlights the shift in belief among religious leaders. While John 7:48 questions the faith of rulers and Pharisees, Acts 6:7 notes that a great company of priests became obedient to the faith.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 49, 46, 1, 20, 21, 'knoweth not the law', 'Wisdom and Knowledge Contrast', 'This connection highlights the contrast between those who are perceived as wise and knowledgeable and those who are considered cursed for not knowing the law. Both passages emphasize the idea that worldly wisdom fails to recognize God, suggesting a deeper understanding is required beyond mere knowledge.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 49, 43, 9, 34, 34, 'knoweth not the law', 'Judgment of the Unlearned', 'This connection highlights the condemnation of those who lack understanding of the law. In both passages, there is a theme of judgment against individuals perceived as sinful or ignorant.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 49, 43, 9, 40, 40, 'knoweth not the law', 'Blindness to the Law', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual blindness. In John 7:49, the people are described as cursed for not knowing the law, while in John 9:40, the Pharisees question their own blindness, suggesting a lack of understanding of the law''s implications.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 49, 46, 3, 18, 20, 'this people who knoweth not the law', 'Wisdom and Foolishness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between worldly wisdom and spiritual understanding. John 7:49''s reference to being ''cursed'' for ignorance of the law parallels 1 Corinthians 3:18-20''s assertion that worldly wisdom is ultimately foolishness with God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 49, 59, 3, 13, 18, 'knoweth not the law', 'Wisdom and Knowledge Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of knowledge and wisdom. John 7:49 speaks of those who do not know the law as cursed, while James 3:13-18 contrasts true wisdom with earthly wisdom, highlighting the need for understanding and righteousness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 49, 23, 5, 21, 21, 'knoweth not the law', 'Wisdom and Ignorance in Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the folly of those who rely on their own understanding rather than the law. The ''wise in their own eyes'' in Isaiah parallels the ''people who knoweth not the law'' in John, highlighting a theme of misguided judgment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 49, 23, 28, 14, 14, 'this people who knoweth not the law', 'Cursing the Ignorant Rulers', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of ignorance among leaders. John 7:49 refers to the people who do not know the law as cursed, while Isaiah 28:14 addresses scornful men ruling over the people, suggesting a failure in understanding and guiding them.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 50, 43, 19, 39, 39, 'he that came to Jesus by night', 'Nicodemus'' Night Encounter', 'Both passages emphasize Nicodemus'' initial visit to Jesus at night, highlighting his evolving role. The reference to him in both contexts underscores his significance in the narrative surrounding Jesus'' life and death.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 50, 43, 3, 1, 2, 'he that came to Jesus by night', 'Connection of Nicodemus'' Encounter', 'Both passages emphasize Nicodemus'' visit to Jesus by night, highlighting his role as a Pharisee and ruler. This connection illustrates his initial curiosity and recognition of Jesus'' divine authority.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 51, 20, 18, 13, 13, 'judge any man, before it hear him', 'Judgment and Hearing', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of hearing before making judgments. John 7:51 questions the legality of judging without hearing, while Proverbs 18:13 states that answering before hearing is folly.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 51, 5, 1, 17, 17, 'judge any man, before it hear him', 'Judgment and Hearing in Law', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of hearing a case before making a judgment. John 7:51 questions the fairness of judging without hearing, while Deuteronomy 1:17 instructs to hear all parties in judgment. This connection highlights the principle of due process in legal matters.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 51, 5, 19, 15, 19, 'Doth our law judge any man', 'Judgment and Witnesses Connection', 'This connection highlights the importance of due process in judgment. Both passages emphasize the necessity of hearing and establishing facts before making a judgment, underscoring the principle of justice.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 51, 44, 23, 3, 3, 'judge any man, before it hear him', 'Judgment and Legal Process', 'This connection highlights the theme of lawful judgment in both passages. John 7:51 questions the fairness of judging without hearing, while Acts 23:3 condemns a judgment that violates the law.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 51, 5, 17, 6, 6, 'judge any man, before it hear him', 'Judgment and Witnesses Connection', 'This connection highlights the importance of hearing and knowing before judgment. Both passages emphasize the necessity of proper testimony and due process in legal matters.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 52, 43, 7, 41, 41, 'out of Galilee ariseth no prophet', 'Galilee and Prophetic Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the skepticism surrounding Jesus'' origins from Galilee. The question of whether a prophet can arise from Galilee is directly linked to the doubts expressed about Christ''s legitimacy as coming from the same region.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 52, 43, 1, 46, 46, 'out of Galilee ariseth no prophet', 'Perception of Galilee and Nazareth', 'This connection highlights the skepticism surrounding Jesus'' origins. Both passages emphasize the belief that no prophet arises from Galilee or Nazareth, reflecting a common prejudice against these regions.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 52, 23, 9, 1, 2, 'out of Galilee ariseth no prophet', 'Galilee and Prophetic Light', 'This connection highlights the mention of Galilee in both passages. John 7:52 asserts that no prophet arises from Galilee, while Isaiah 9:1-2 speaks of a great light shining in Galilee, suggesting a prophetic significance associated with the region.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 52, 40, 4, 15, 16, 'out of Galilee ariseth no prophet', 'Galilee''s Role in Prophecy', 'This connection highlights the perception of Galilee as a place of little significance in John, contrasted with Matthew''s depiction of it as a source of light and fulfillment of prophecy. Both passages emphasize the importance of Galilee in the context of prophetic revelation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 52, 1, 19, 9, 9, NULL, 'Judgment and Rejection Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of a figure perceived as unworthy. In John 7:52, the question of Galilee''s prophets reflects a judgment against Jesus, while Genesis 19:9 shows the crowd''s hostility towards Lot, who is also judged for his outsider status.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 52, 2, 2, 14, 14, 'Art thou also of Galilee?', 'Connection Between Moses and Prophets', 'This connection highlights the skepticism towards leaders from Galilee, paralleling Moses'' rejection as a leader by his own people. Both passages emphasize the questioning of authority and the recognition of a prophet''s role. The mention of Galilee in John reflects a similar dismissal of Moses'' leadership in Exodus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 52, 11, 22, 24, 24, 'out of Galilee ariseth no prophet', 'Prophetic Authority and Origin', 'This connection highlights the skepticism towards prophets based on their origins. In John 7:52, the assertion that no prophet arises from Galilee parallels the challenge to Micaiah''s prophetic authority in 1 Kings 22:24, where Zedekiah questions the legitimacy of the Spirit''s message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 53, 19, 33, 10, 10, 'every man went unto his own house', 'Divine Authority Over Human Plans', 'This connection highlights the contrast between human actions and divine sovereignty. While John 7:53 notes that people returned to their own houses, Psalms 33:10 emphasizes that the Lord nullifies human counsel, suggesting that human intentions are ultimately subject to God''s will.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 53, 18, 5, 12, 13, 'every man went unto his own house', 'Craftiness and Disappointment', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals returning to their own ways after being confronted. Both passages emphasize the futility of human plans against divine wisdom, as seen in the phrase ''every man went unto his own house'' and the disappointment of the crafty in Job.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 53, 19, 76, 5, 5, NULL, 'Connection of Sleep and Departure', 'This connection highlights the theme of departure and rest. In John 7:53, the phrase ''every man went unto his own house'' suggests a return to a place of rest, while Psalms 76:5 speaks of those who have ''slept their sleep,'' indicating a state of inactivity or rest.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 7, 53, 19, 76, 10, 10, NULL, 'Connection of Human Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of human behavior in response to divine authority. In John 7:53, individuals return to their own houses, suggesting a retreat from conflict, while Psalms 76:10 emphasizes how human wrath can ultimately serve to praise God, indicating a complex relationship between human actions and divine purpose.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
